Data Preprocessing¶

The Grenoble challenge (http://egc2017.imag.fr/defi/) provides several datasets.

  • Données_Défi_EGC2017-J1-J2
    The data given to the competitor to create the model. It is divided into two datasets: Jeu1 and Jeu2. Each dataset is further divided into the features X containing tree information, geolocation information, and the measurement y.
  • Données_Défi_EGC2017-J3
    The data for the competition. Competitor shold predict this data based on their model and send the prediction to the organizer.

Load the data¶

In [2]:
X_tree_1=pd.read_table('.//data//Données_Défi_EGC2017-J1-J2//Jeu1//X_tree_egc_t1.csv',sep=';',engine='python')
X_loc_1=pd.read_table('.//data//Données_Défi_EGC2017-J1-J2//Jeu1//X_geoloc_egc_t1.csv',sep=';',engine='python')
y_1=pd.read_table('.//data//Données_Défi_EGC2017-J1-J2//Jeu1//Y_tree_egc_t1.csv',sep=';',engine='python')

X_tree_2=pd.read_table('.//data//Données_Défi_EGC2017-J1-J2//Jeu2//X_tree_egc_t2.csv',sep=';',engine='python')
X_loc_2=pd.read_table('.//data//Données_Défi_EGC2017-J1-J2//Jeu2//X_geoloc_egc_t2.csv',sep=';',engine='python')
y_2=pd.read_table('.//data//Données_Défi_EGC2017-J1-J2//Jeu2//Y_tree_egc_t2.csv',sep=';',engine='python')

Combine the data¶

In [3]:
# features X
frames = [X_tree_1,X_tree_2]
X_tree = pd.concat(frames)
frames = [X_loc_1,X_loc_2]
X_loc = pd.concat(frames)
X = pd.concat([X_tree,X_loc], axis=1)

# measurement y
frames = [y_1,y_2]
y = pd.concat(frames)

Separate training set and test set¶

In [4]:
from sklearn.cross_validation import train_test_split

# separate the dataset into train and test set
# use stratified sampling to maintain the distribution of the class
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2,random_state=37,stratify=y['Default or not'])

Data exploration and data cleansing¶

Below is the description of each attributes:

Name Description
ADR_SECTEUR area code
ANNEEDEPLANTATION year
ANNEEREALISATIONDIAGNOSTIC year of diagnostic
ANNEETRAVAUXPRECONISESDIAG year recommended for next diagnostic
CODE ID of a tree
CODE_PARENT parent's ID of a tree
CODE_PARENT_DESC location of parent
DIAMETREARBREAUNMETRE diameter of a strain in interval
ESPECE species of the tree
FREQUENTATIONCIBLE whether the tree is near a road
GENRE_BOTA the name of genre of the tree
IDENTIFIANTPLU an ID given by some urban plan
INTITULEPROTECTIONPLU a title given by some urban plan
NOTEDIAGNOSTIC diagnostic notes
PRIORITEDERENOUVELLEMENT year of priority of diagnostics
RAISONDEPLANTATION reason for tree planting
REMARQUES other information of the tree
SOUS_CATEGORIE ID of subcategory (4 unique values)
SOUS_CATEGORIE_DESC Description of subcategory
STADEDEDEVELOPPEMENT stage of tree development
STADEDEVELOPPEMENTDIAG stage of tree development during diagnosis
TRAITEMENTCHENILLES priority of treatment
TRAVAUXPRECONISESDIAG recommendation after safety diagnosis
TROTTOIR tree near sidewalk or not
TYPEIMPLANTATIONPLU how trees are planted
VARIETE variety of the trees
VIGUEUR tree vigor
coord_x X coordinate
coord_y Y coordinate
Default or not whether the tree is sick or not
Collet whether the collar of the tree is sick or not
Houppier whether the crown of the tree is sick or not
Racine whether the root of the tree is sick or not
Tronc whether the trunk of the tree is sick or not

Remove ID attribute¶
In [41]:
# identify the ID attribute, characterized by having a big percentage of unique values
for col in list(X_train):
    num_unique = X_train[col].nunique()
    # attribute name, number of unique values, percentage of unique values
    print("%40s\t%d\t%f" % (col,num_unique,(num_unique / len(X_train[col] * 100))))
    
# CODE is an ID attribute
# coord_x and coord_y are not ID attribute, since it represents a coordinate

Bivariate Analysis¶
  • remove two attributes that has a high similarity (if two attributes a high correlation, it means that both of them represents the same concept, therefore we need to remove one of them to avoid bias during the modelling)
  • similarity can be calculated by calculating the correlation if the attributes are numeric, or test of independence (chi-square test) if the attributes are nominal
  • plot the geolocation attributes and mark tree with disease to visualize

Class Attribute¶

Univariate Analysis¶

Analyze whether class imbalance exists in the class attribute.

In [51]:
# function to print a summary of class attribute

def print_class_summary(class_attr):
    col_names = class_attr.columns
    not_sick_array = np.array(0)
    sick_array = np.array(1)
    for col_name in col_names:
        not_sick,sick = y_train[col_name].value_counts()
        sick_array = np.append(sick_array,sick)
        not_sick_array = np.append(not_sick_array,not_sick)
    col_names = np.append("Class Attribute",col_names)
    summary = np.column_stack((col_names,not_sick_array,sick_array))
    for i in range(len(summary)):
        print("%15s\t%10s\t%10s" % (summary[i,0],str(summary[i,1]),summary[i,2]))
    return;

Multivariate Analysis¶

Analyze whether a pattern exists in the class attribute. We suspect that if one of the partial class attribute (Collet, Houppier, Racine, Tronc) is sick, then the Default or Not is always sick.

In [53]:
pattern = y_train['Default or not'] == (y_train['Collet'] | y_train['Houppier'] | y_train['Racine'] | y_train['Tronc'])
In [54]:
pattern.value_counts()
Out[54]:
True    12300
dtype: int64

The result shows that there is a rule in the data, if any of the partial class attribute (Collet, Houppier, Racine, or Tronc) is sick, then the Default or Not is always sick.

We can use this information when predicting the data. Therefore to predict Default or Not, we can predict the other partial class attribute instead. However, since the partial class attribute has a very heavy imbalance, we think it's better to predict the Default or Not using classification method directly. We will use the partial class attribute using clustering to predict whether a contagious disease in detected in some are of the map.

In [76]:
def identify_cluster(X):
    # Compute DBSCAN
    db.fit(X)
    core_samples_mask = np.zeros_like(db.labels_, dtype=bool)
    core_samples_mask[db.core_sample_indices_] = True
    labels = db.labels_
    # Number of clusters in labels, ignoring noise if present.
    n_clusters_ = len(set(labels)) - (1 if -1 in labels else 0)    
    # Black removed and is used for noise instead.
    unique_labels = set(labels)
    colors = [plt.cm.Spectral(each)
              for each in np.linspace(0, 1, len(unique_labels))]
    for k, col in zip(unique_labels, colors):
        if k == -1:
            # Black used for noise.
            col = [0, 0, 0, 1]

        class_member_mask = (labels == k)

        xy = X[class_member_mask & core_samples_mask]
        
        plt.plot(xy.iloc[:, 0].values, xy.iloc[:, 1].values, 'o', markerfacecolor=tuple(col),
                 markeredgecolor='k', markersize=14)

        xy = X[class_member_mask & ~core_samples_mask]
        plt.plot(xy.iloc[:, 0].values, xy.iloc[:, 1].values, 'o', markerfacecolor=tuple(col),
                 markeredgecolor='k', markersize=6)
        
        fig = plt.gcf()
        
        default_size = fig.get_size_inches()
        fig.set_size_inches(default_size[0]*1.2,default_size[1]*1.2)
    plt.title('Estimated number of clusters: %d' % n_clusters_)
    plt.show()
    return;
